The tenant of Bakal: The poles are heating up, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing old man walked out the door of the customer center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying under his arm a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and his son who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation has increased the rent to these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of second category 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works with solid fuel," shows finger on the new contract of his son the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed it anyway," he explains in anger and half resigned.
The citizen association of apartments BytyOKD.cz, which has described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published explaining the method to follow to claim.
But man reacts to this by a gesture of the hand.
"One says this, the other says something else" by frowning at the eyebrows.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory for deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most of the apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
Aktualne.cz has therefore decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
A single press and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You do not have time to read your number "157" as your number is already starting to light up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second, it's your turn.
After a brief moment, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems like everywhere - repair requests, insurance events and more.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been collecting mail with the new leases in their mailbox since around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special window for new rents has been open to the public since November 18.
“It’s been running for almost a week, so it’s still in the test,” she replies, after a moment of hesitation, the employee behind the counter when the client presents herself as a journalist.
The derangement and former Bakal miner apartments are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of the parliament and a native of the Ostrava region, Lubomir Zaoralek, of the Social Democrats, reported this quite strongly before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
“Twenty years after them, I want a new floor.”
"They didn't even change a put...n board in the toilets, the man mentioned in the introduction is relieved.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to make sure they will receive a rebate on the new rent price if they sign up now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a refund of half of the amount of the rent that will be received by other tenants who will have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" window of Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by the questions.
"Among the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent," the employee said.
And yet RPG covers both on its website and in the showcases of individual interviews on rents when necessary.
If the two parties do not agree on the rent, an independent court will make the decision.
“This is not a threat, it’s just to inform about the unique and legitimate way to act legally,” the company said on its website.
"No one's going to court here," one of the Byty RPG employees thinks, and the man in the street in front of the customer center is right.
“I have 13,000 crowns of retirement and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don’t have enough to go to court,” he said.
The employee suddenly feels uneasy.
"We'll see".
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and therefore people wait," she said.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase in the rent.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in the apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this is expected to be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the padded chairs of the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
“The increase in rent in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31,200 apartments, or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments.”
"And it will always be at most 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," the screen says.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really very low sum of 19.66 Czech crowns per m2," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but progressive increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the increase in rents (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rent increase agreement have priority.
The kindergarten is also part of offices have included the architects.
the Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected that it also houses a mini kindergarten with everything you need - colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, children of Arch. design employees have been able to go there.
The architectural project company Arch. Design., whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has been designing its mini business kindergarten since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, mostly from a child-bearing age, and it was important to it that women architects and project managers can return to work quickly.
At the same time as reduced-time employment contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine work that takes care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini kindergarten is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme for Human Resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding (in the amount of 2.8 thousand Czech crowns), they were able to purchase equipment and devices and after two years to provide qualified personnel and start-up.
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and it was the company Economy rating that helped to make the request for staffing.
Childcare is provided by a qualified staff, all day a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children. children can go to kindergarten without age limit but they have more than three times most.
As it is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more that are replaced.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use this school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although it is an individual care and education, the program of the mini kindergarten is comparable to that for preschool education.
The children do not just play there but quality education is also assured - from the beginning to the preparation at the school benches we teach English.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and not have the stress of a delay to pick up the children in a school away from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that a natural relationship of loyalty is created between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus registered among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and who are friendly towards the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the locals the nickname House in Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is typical of Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house unfolds its dream lines, pleasant colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In the course of a more detailed observation we see the geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced by it.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, railings, decorative elements of the doors, the eyelet and the slats.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in the Passeig de Gracia shopping street at number 43, was born from the construction of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place over two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building another brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-family house was not conceived by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of mosaic for the facade were born.
Other artists and creators have also worked on the facade.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Mila house and Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the house hot right after its finish because of its organic forms "the House in Bones".
Others, in view of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, called it "the house that dances".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time,with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree tilt seems bizarre.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction directives of that time and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he got the permission from the city to build, knowing, of course, that the data carried on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the municipal council was horrified and demanded changes.
For example, members of the city council did not like the fact that the pillars of the construction were impinging on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two upper floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third one a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of linking spaces.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit itself to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi’s play with light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with the wells of lights.
The two-color play gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house which was listed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and they expanded the scope of visits to common areas and attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the price of entry into Gaudi's other constructions in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you need to quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
