Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
The fear of their child leads more and more people to think about watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases such as that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of the little Anicka touched a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying but only another way to reduce the likelihood that there will be another tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of the company MACro Weil, which is one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear such a thing on him, he will get rid of it.
“Even the smallest ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations,” says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is highly questionable.
"If this is a pre-arranged abduction, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
“Right now, it’s the phone.”
“As soon as the tracking devices are developed, they (criminals) will look for them too because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign.”
“In such cases, the criminals will always be ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, she admits that such devices can help with an unprepared assault by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is in regular emission after a certain period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
'The most expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself in an elongated position without moving,' says Cech.
According to him, so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special software.
The problem with today's tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn on a pendant the size of a matchbox or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina from the company Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll realize it after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracking cars.
