To this day, I benefit from the contacts I have gained through the contests.
The franchise sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun for the place of winner of the contest of the best individual Entrepreneur.
The winner of the Best Individual Entrepreneur competition for the past year was Lukas Pytloun, a 28-year-old entrepreneur.
His adventure to success is like in a movie.
Lukas Pytloun liked to travel.
And abroad, he realized that in Liberec there was a lack of quality accommodation at a reasonable price.
From his savings on what he had earned while working abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small building of 5 apartments half demolished.
Knowing that he was still a student in his third year of graduate school, it was a courageous action.
“The relationship between the quality and price of accommodation in our region made me want to do something,” says Lucas Pytloun.
He began renting the first reconstructed apartment to foreign workers.
He reinvests the profit in the building that he transformed into a pension with 54 beds.
Since then, his entrepreneurial activity has allowed him to open in Liberec 4 guesthouses, two stylish restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of almost 300 beds of all accommodation categories.
The most comfortable of them was until recently the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year there was another one of the same quality.
“We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrova U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other candidates for the Pytloun hotels franchise showed up,” the number one entrepreneur of the past year.
"And for the sale of the license for the operation of a large-scale hotel, the victory in the Entrepreneur of the Year competition has served well," Pytloun adds with gratitude.
The victory brought him more popularity and to be known in Liberec and its surroundings.
“People recognized me on the streets, often congratulated me and, I have to say, it was very nice,” he recalls.
He recommends participation in this contest to all those who strive to do something.
It is not necessary to win but any opportunity to be visible is good.
He says he uses his contacts and knowledge to this day that he could not have obtained otherwise.
“With those I met through the competition I started to maintain business relationships regularly.
According to him, the success-related reputation also had an impact on employees.
And he's about 70.
“I see in their homes above all the loyalty and pride of being committed to something that has been generally acknowledged.”
“It’s not, and by far, the only result of my personal work, but the result of a good work of all of us together.
“Only my name is pushed forward,” says Lucas Pytloun with modesty.
