At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public competition
In the building of the Land Fund in Plzen, the anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives passed the handcuffs to the local contractor and real estate trader Lubos.
It had sought to manipulate precisely a public call for tenders for the settlement of a request for restitution in such a way that the proposed land would be obtained by a specific candidate.
He had to pay Lubos G. half a million kroner.
"For the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for an insider's offence in the context of a call for tenders and a public competition," Antonie Zelena, head of Plzen's Public Prosecutor's Office, told the newspaper Pravo, noting that it is forbidden to provide further explanations as the investigation is ongoing.
Police released the 46-year-old entrepreneur after 24 hours.
To know how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate with regard to so little official information.
In a question from Pravo, Lubomira Cerna, spokeswoman for the Land Fund, said that the police had actually made an arrest in Plzen in a separate workplace during the public competition.
"It was a customer and under no circumstances an employee," she said.
According to Cerna, the real name of the public tender is "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land under the Land Act" and is put in place when several eligible candidates appear.
“These people propose, as part of the appeal, a higher value of their right to restitutions that must be settled before the value of the land is announced.”
"According to the proposed rights, a classification of purchasers is established and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights," the Fund's spokesman explained.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information regarding the persons who had registered for the call and since he himself is also a beneficiary person because having purchased a large number of restitution rights, he had proposed to the field candidates not to participate in the competition.
And he was probably cashing in on the fact that he was retiring.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts far above the standards at the FdT (Land Fund).
He was involved in the case of former head of the FdT Vaclav Sankot, who was prosecuted for editing land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been made.
Lubos G. had obtained, for example, land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place and place where the access road to the industrial area of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was forced to accept because otherwise it risked putting the construction at risk by blocking the land.
