Czech children get drunk on rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very gently.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated at the hospital for recidivism are no exception.
This is a result of the experience of doctors who experience cases similar to hospital admissions in children's departments.
“Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk.”
“The trend is really strong alcohol,” says Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children’s department at Horovice Hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to chip a bottle of papa in the cupboard, it's sometimes whiskey but it's the fernet and vodka that prevail."
"Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not feel it," the head of the department said.
Eva Jurinova, spokesman for the Motol hospital, is also right.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
"Today, it is fashionable alcohol, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought back from the house," Jurinova added.
According to the Pelikan Head of Department, seeing drunk children between the ages of thirteen and fourteen admitted to the hospital is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced for ten years precisely in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wide surroundings completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized like this four times
