Only cases with a poisoning rod requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are after emergency care brought home by their parents or the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan there are three seasonal waves that can be counted on: the day of the witches, the New Year and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink despite bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
"Of course, I experienced the day of witches an admission of 7 drunk children at one time," Pelikan said.
The drunk child who spent the night in the hospital in detox under medical control is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from the "woody mouth".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
“They are better off because they have a great evening and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them.”
“They’re just amazed at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils the good mood of patients at least with the note to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and hospitalization on intensive care bed can go up to tens of thousands of crowns.
"From time to time, I have applied this as a means of education by counting on these children how much their drinking has cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to pay for a single evening," Pelikan added.
