Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two of the five L-159 aircraft, against which the Ministry of Defence exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off on Tuesday for Seville in Spain where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that devices of this type become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were previously in service in the Czech Army and were in flight.
The remaining Lestrois aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
They are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the company Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the Vodochody aircraft is currently unknown.
“The L-159 single-seater aircraft planned for exchange have been taken on long-stored aircraft without causing additional charges or investment for the Ministry of Defence.”
"The two-seater L-159 T1s were exchanged in the state," Pejsek told Pravo.
He said that the army will not be left without a two-seater since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159s into two two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek, EADS is committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of certain Alliance countries.
“The contract clearly states that the L-159 aircraft will be EADS and will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries.”
“It is therefore up to the person who is considering how to do this,” Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced, some time ago, that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not initiate a call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
Defence management argued that the exchange would ensure a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aéro Vodochody and used only 24 of them, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected as part of a European-wide tender and under no circumstances by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
An index longer than the ring is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have the index longer than the annular are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, particularly for men before age 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo prostate cancer testing, including combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a shorter right-hand index than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the ring, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60, the risk reduction reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is testosterone that helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but does not think, it seems, that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
