Five years ago, a huge amount of oil came out of an oil pipeline that exploded in the huge swamp.
Fishermen living in the small town of Bodo now have to row for six hours to reach the fishing waters: The Ogoni country located in the heart of the Niger Delta is considered one of the most polluted regions in the world.
The full extent of the ravages comes to the fore when one traverses the mangrove swamps crossed by streams.
Instead of clear water, the motorboat splits a scalding brown water; whoever dips his hand into it removes any oil-covered water.
The roots of the small mangrove emerge from the ground like licorice sticks. The isolated palm trees sadly let their palms hang.
We look in vain for the clouds of birds, as we usually find in wet areas: As soon as the outboard engine stops, a phantom silence falls on this former paradise that looks like a service station by the smell it emits.
"What is happening here is a war against the environment," says Mr. Celestine Akpobari in a sad tone: "Our life is characterized by a permanent danger in terms of health."
The comparison of wars is made.
The region where the Ogoni live is a field of battle besieged for decades: more than 60 years ago, the first European explorers penetrated here; the first resistance was organized in the 1980s by the writer Ken Saro-Wiwa. it was later executed. In 1993, the Shell group had to be employed to disrupt its production activities.
Even today, the return to the Ogoni country is forbidden to this company: While more than 2 million barrels of black gold are pumped daily through more than 5000 wells and 7000 kilometers of oil pipelines in the entire Delta region, three times as large as Switzerland, the oil fields of the Ogoni country are too unexploited, because the situation is too untapped.
Every few hundred meters stand in the water of the steel trettles like bizarre sculptures: It is very affectionately referred to as "Christmas trees" the heads of drilling holes.
They are up to 50 years old, most of them are gnawed by corrosion to the mark.
Akpobari estimates that a drilling head of this nature breaks from time to time into pieces, as a constant flow of crude oil flows into the water.
According to experts, more than two billion liters have spilled onto the ecosystem in 50 years: Every year, the amount of oil equivalent to that which flowed into the sea during the accident of the super-tanker "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago off Alaska, one of the greatest disasters in the environment.
Who should bear the responsibility for persistent environmental pollution? the answer to this question divides the actors.
For the Shell Group, the sabotage and siphoning of oil pipelines is responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution, while environmentalists regard explosions of drilling heads and drilled oil pipelines as the main causes.
In 2008, U.S. researcher Richard Steiner criticized the Shell Group for applying substantially less stringent safety standards to Nigeria than anywhere else in the world: Only the rate of driver failure is "far higher than allure".
Some forms emerge from the mangroves in a place that, seen from a distance, looks like an abandoned workshop, full of boulders and installed outdoors: They are completely naked and covered with boulders up to the neck.
A fire sparkles under one of the many tunnels that are sometimes connected to the pipes, sometimes scattered without a motive on the site must be spotted: a small underground refinery.
The crude oil is heated in the barrel for several hours, says Michael, the team leader.
At first, the gasoline enters a container through pipes, then at the end of the pipe the drops of kerosene fall and diesel is finally obtained.
That’s how Michael and his four collaborators produce four 300-litre diesel barrels a day: “This brings us 34,000 Naira,” about $22.
The people of the Delta are taking advantage of the chronic fuel shortage in the largest oil-producing country in black Africa.
There is only one refinery in Nigeria.
Illegal refiners can sell at a cheaper price than the ridiculously low one of just 40 cents per liter of Diesel: Because they buy their raw material for free.
According to experts, the country is losing at least 16 million litres of crude oil in the entire Niger Delta as a result of the "protectors" who are putting the oil pipeline network into drilling throughout the Ogoni country.
Only a small fraction of the raw material temporarily stored is illegally purified: The organized crime networks, which also include high-ranking politicians and military members, charge the lion’s share in tankers and bridle it into the global market.
Activist Akpobari believes that the debate over whether to attribute the environmental disaster or rather subversive activities to the population or the lax mode of production is purely academic.
“If oil companies were not perceived as intruders and if the foundations of fishermen’s lives were not so deeply destroyed, there would be no sabotage, no theft and no illegal refineries.”
But, in the meantime, Ogoni's relationship with Shell has deteriorated so much that it was no longer a question of the group's withdrawal. "maybe operators with other nationalities, like the Chinese, will turn out to be better."
Then Michael gets nervous.
“It’s high time you got rid of it,” announces the hard-working oil worker.
"Soldiers can appear at any time."
If the illegal refiners are surprised by the special units of the armed forces, they will certainly not be arrested, but at most they will offer them bribes.
Even soldiers, especially from the north of the country, intend to enjoy the raw material like all Nigerians.
"In any case, this little thing has brought our country down," Akpori laments.
