Is the Splatter film an artificial film?
Director Nicolas Winding Refn explores the limits of the ancient genre thanks to his film, "Walhalla Rising", the warrior's epic.
What audience did the Danish director Nicolas Winding Refn think of when shooting "Walhalla Rising"?
A Viking warrior (Mads Mikkelsen) possessing only one eye is taken prisoner; he frees the brutes from his executioner and, with an almost supernatural force, eliminates his opponents one after another. This seems ideal for young male spectators in search of a bloody action, precisely because our hero uses evil methods.
On the other hand, until the end of the film, the blind man does not say a word about his real name. Even the other characters let escape, at most, by way of one or two sentences a few terrible cries of agony.
Otherwise, we say nothing and we celebrate in the incredibly beautiful mountain landscape of Scotland that is the setting of the Viking world, about a thousand years ago.
This would be ideal plus mature filmmakers with an interest in existentialism and excellent traveling.
When a film targets multiple target groups, it is a pity that they mutually exclude each other.
Since the release of Pusher, director Winding Refn is seen as a kind of Danish Quentin Tarantin, but he refuses to bring a little more mood to the mainstream or introduce a little less brutality to art and experimental cinema.
Most art-cinema enthusiasts must experience horror in the face of the brain that spreads all around and to the intestines.
Action film lovers die of boredom when the blind man embarks, for reasons that can be freely interpreted, with a group of violent Christian missionaries on a ship bound for Jerusalem; they are drowned for an eternity by calm and fog before the crew arrives in America.
It is not surprising then that "Walhalla Rising" did not find any film distributors in Germany and that it exists only in DVD format.
It is above all because of the magnificent images of misery that has deserved some attention, but also because the image of a thrilling film, from time to time, hides behind a pretentious and bloody appearance.
It is not a dialogue in this film, nor a coherent action, everything is atmosphere, a feverish dream transformed into film.
The spectator cannot escape.
Refn barely gives him a moment of relaxation and slowly cuts his throat with glacial images and a gloomy soundtrack, but above all with an elusive hatred that springs from the hearts of the characters.
Only a young blond boy, who stands faithfully next to the blind man, preserves a certain innocence, all the others are animated by anger.
More than anything, the blind hero whose mobiles are never known, but who returns from hell at any time to fight enemies and temporarily allies by turning into a warrior, is perhaps sent from the devil himself.
It represents decay, but perhaps also, only for those who are, in any case, rotten.
"Walhalla Rising" is an enigmatic film that one can hate or admire, which has as its purpose the angst, enthusiasm and amazement.
A traumatic experience.
