The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications regarding a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a stand on this issue, let alone submit to the agency's controls.
On the night of September 5-6, 2007, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the banks of the Euphrates; the largest city located nearby is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
Its name appears in the IAEA documents, because it is a question of the reactor that Syria built, it appears with the help of North Korea in stone parallelepiped, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electric current.
According to a briefing by the US intelligence services, the CIA, dating from late April 2008,the current reactor, known as the neighboring locality, el-Kibar, would be well suited to produce plutonium, which would allow the manufacture of atomic weapons.
However, this technique has been used since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a presentation video featuring blurry satellite images.
Through computer-assisted animation, it indicated the likely location of each reactor component before the destruction of the power plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even the interior of it.
It appears that the reactor was about to be commissioned, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, there is barely more information available than at the time, and even, with time, the mystery thickens more and more.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that prior to this attack, the CIA was certain that Syria had built a reactor at el-Kibar, but had little evidence that the country was developing “an active nuclear weapons program.”
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and speak only of a “presumed reactor,” even though they consider the CIA’s presentation to be “plausible.”
They lack tangible evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he made sure he was dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior UN diplomat gave only a laconic response in the summer, saying the IAEA had “sufficient documents to ask questions.”
The Syrians certainly hastily removed the rubble of the “unused military building” and proceeded to methodically flatten the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of man-made uranium in el-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA received satellite images from commercial providers from a member state showing the moment that directly followed the attack. it appears that the latter are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for IAEA to establish their authenticity in an objective manner.
Syria has always maintained that it has never carried out a secret atomic program and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus claims that the uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after analyzing the particles, calling it implausible.
Since then, Damas has refused to discuss this, as well as satellite imagery.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to carry out a second inspection of the al-Kibar site and refuses access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel remains stubbornly silent.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then-Prime Minister in office at the time of the attack, recently said: “We will never comment on this.”
Thus, the investigation into this case has been ongoing since June 2008 without a result being achieved, and it "is increasingly becoming a serious credibility issue of the Agency", as acknowledged by a senior Western diplomat in service at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna, ultimately a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Arms.
The IAEA believes that in order to make progress, the existence of the other three facilities that must have a "functional relationship" with the alleged reactor must be clarified.
So far, the inspectors have neither indicated which facilities are involved here, nor what their function is or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the newspaper "S<0xC3><0xBC>ddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also under the name of neighboring cities.
The Independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington has identified these locations and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would most likely be one of the suspicious objects.
It may be located in a military base or directly adjacent to it; that is exactly why Syria refuses access to IAEA inspectors from all three sites.
In Vienna, it is claimed that Syrians fear that the inspection group is in fact spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it is information provided by US secret agents that has attracted the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have made shuttles between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped in order to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could "serve for fuel production."
It would have "no indication of sensitive activities", such as uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes that are indispensable to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to the non-enriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible hypotheses regarding the following fundamental questions: where uranium should have come from and where plutonium needed to make the bomb would later have been separated.
It is unknown whether the prints, which could hide traces of high value, were stored at all three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with earth have disappeared, no one will have information about the place of storage of the rubble.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located just a few kilometers from al-Kibar on the other side of the Euphrates, examined in 1998 to see if it could be suitable for storing radioactive waste.
In a recent analysis of photos taken by satellite on behalf of the famed Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley established a link between them and the reactor in question.
Satellite images show, however, that Syria has undertaken grounding work at the three suspected sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to those sites.
It may have been a coincidence, but it did not help to dispel the suspicions.
He said in the diplomatic circles that the IAEA spent several months developing a plan for inspections to be carried out there. This plan was supposed to allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. Only the time spent shows how much interest inspectors have in this case.
In the meantime, Damascus has also put an end to this proposal.
