An arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, broadens the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
“That’s why it’s very special, even though it’s far from a truly ‘foreign’ form of life,” said Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday’s online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But researchers have found that the bacterium, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“One wonders what is still possible,” said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in researching life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the find, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could reveal the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms might be able to use other elements to drive biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, might not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Institute for Planetary and Space Science Research, Openton University-Unireich.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element for another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
It was not a fortuitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances might be able to replace each other.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus.”
“As a result, organizations struggle to distinguish these elements separately.”
"But arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and somehow erases the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that some form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of Earth's existence, she says; so the researchers hypothesized that early life forms could have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways of forming life, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
