The lion is ready to blush again, the restructuring of MGM is waiting for the final green light of the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start all over again.
A New York federal bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially leased the plan “pre-packaged” by creditors that about $5 billion of debt would be wiped out; paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and shows.
With Thursday’s decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, there are no longer any legal obstacles before MGM to get back on track under the tutelage of the founders of Entertainment Spyglass, Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the CEOs of what will be a studio.
The staff will be reduced to about 320 out of 400 initially.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has completed a $500 million credit facility, planned to fund MGM's new operations and productions.
It is currently distributed under license by the investment bank, which is itself facing $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The studio’s restructuring process began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to place its finances as it did not have the means to pay interest amounting to $300 million per year.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO of Enron and a recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to solve MGM’s financial difficulties and satisfy the studio’s more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed, at the end of 2009, to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the $2 billion more that the creditors were looking for.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be done again as the MGM team had started working on a restructuring plan which, after months of disagreements and internal debates, was finally approved by the creditors in late October.
When MGM officially exits bankruptcy in the following weeks, companies Moelis and Cooper receive multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper’s companies, which have raised $375,000 per month for their company’s management services, will receive a “success premium” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to relaunch the production of MGM, which released only one film this year, and set up an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released starting in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on The Hobbit, with Warner Bros.
The studio is to make a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its part in these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM’s debt, has attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the main shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not resulted in an agreement.
