Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Department of Justice have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case involving a former campaign assistant and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican from Nevada who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign’s office said he was “very happy” with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed that Senator Ensign is no longer under investigation and that he has no intention of maintaining any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, according to which there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign had conspired to violate a federal criminal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first reported in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to gain the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, with regard to the matter of the se.
Mrs. Hampton once served as treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited for one year by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems to contradict the so-called prohibition of the revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that was made public, “there appears to be prima facie evidence of a plot to violate and substantial violation of the law of the revolving door,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the departmental judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks filed by its public integrity section, including last year's rulings against it.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the director general of citizens for accountability and ethics in Washington, a defense group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s senior counsel, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and a follow-up the next day, telling him the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, had "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The electoral commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada corporation that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as lobbyist, Ensign’s chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was “beating” the Home Office on a disputed issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton in lobbying.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth-ranked Republican in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department's lead and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
