How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be noted that Merkel’s position is not an error in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another constraint of the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future must be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, in Germany one begins to speculate on the three possible outcomes of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, although now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third, a new design of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to countries that violate them, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and it has long been defined, therefore now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought it should do (plans of fiscal rigour and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow of the Central European country was when Merkel hardly extended the decision to save Greece.
From that moment on it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion and the published opinion were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the Union's treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time force private lenders to bear a share of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although slightly sweetened, was approved and in the following months we should be witnessing the process of Union reform that will make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think to cross.
And she tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we cannot agree too much, from that date on the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely penalized, they may be forced to declare themselves in default and, in this case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany points out to us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just a matter of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked to do is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring us greater peace of mind.
And that we know how to seize the opportunity that we were given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticisms, the path has been opened to the thesis that we must put order at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to be moving it.
And among the possibilities that are envisaged, one cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone too full of unserious countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that she had warned us.
