The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, if not quite common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that emerged in the related case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and who in past occasions has condemned a fine to its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mour<0xC3><0xAD>n, and his more educative.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behavior is not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether with these actions one commits a fraud of law; because, in fact, they are actions that are respectful of the regulation of sport, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sports mind.
One of the assets that includes the sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with correct play is to prevent the offending team from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is also not the case.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not settle for what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty.
They were waiting and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders receive from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next match either, as the club could not count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of uncertainty, because the team could be eliminated all of a sudden and apart from that, with this action players complete a penalty game and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the steps, it is not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, of which strategic decisions are nevertheless part, which favor the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without overturning the penalty or escaping it.
Even though the line between genius and the fraud of the law is diffused, on this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, appears to be due to two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way in which to transmit the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
