A global plan to renovate lighting
The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancun a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that corresponds to almost one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to have adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, most of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHGs emitted to the planet would be emitted for light.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to push global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance sheet to be able to stabilize the climate increase to 2 degrees centigrade by 2020 in order to avoid it becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy need is reduced by two more times.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100.
These all-new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
It does not contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place guidelines.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluorocompact bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants, whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
