Avenging hackers and spies on duty
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's do it in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file made up of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those of which Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi's ominously caricatured profile had long been for cabaret artists matter to sketch.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous books.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only what they already know, and which reconfirms what they had already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in spirit) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, as I know, editor at Liberation), who only holds what he recognizes as true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since heads of state can telephone or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have turned into centers of pionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secretive secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put the victims as much in crisis as the "criminals".
But let’s get to the deep nature of what happened.
In the days of Orwell, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is a public domain secret; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that all of Hillary’s secrets were empty.
WikiLeaks has done no wrong to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any reserved information online - it would be like publishing it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential relationships by phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved reports be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore novel, but I am obliged to imagine government agents moving discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable routes, being carriers only of messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding information from them.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: at bottom, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has restored a telegraph on wires (telephones).
The (analog) videotapes had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only make it possible to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, by macro portions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the politics and communication techniques go back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
