Climate: how France is squandering its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the promises of fast-start or early-start financing made by developed countries.
And the big French bedouillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU launched the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, grand side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciable and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had committed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, setting it on track to meet its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years to fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France believes that the financing of "all the new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditures of previous years or to the overall level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to “new and additional” financing.
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses his or her method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> loan equals 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> given.
Obviously, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At the same time, the country should be counted as the borrower's interest rate for its commitments.
But France has only to make such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
It's a nice pass!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is operating a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, she manages to make it appear that she is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely duped...
The early funding chapter is just a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): the question of "additionality" or the way of accounting for loans will not be eluded.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would naturally increase the level of international confidence needed to advance the discussions.
Alert to Pesticides Ingested by Children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (formerly the Movement for Rights and Respect for Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", bought between July and September the foods usually consumed in four meals and a snack in one day by a child of about ten years, in the supermarkets of Paris and Oise.
These standard meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as treats, have been reviewed by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The record is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies from several institutions such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
“Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three proven as certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues that may disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, as encased by the study, shows traces of six chemicals, one of which is banned in France.
The same goes for Kenya’s green beans, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were truffled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk for the consumer of this "contaminant cocktails" is "probably underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "face to the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
